    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1883-08-20T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1883-08-20T00:00:00-05:00" n="484"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d484">
                <head>No. 485.<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Halderman</persName> to Mr.
                            <persName type="to">Frelinghuysen</persName>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Legation of the United States</hi>,<lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Bangkok</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1883-08-20">
                            <hi rend="italic">August</hi> 20, 1883</date>. (Received October
                        8.)</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 53.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The French engineers, headed by Captain Bellion,
                    of the French navy, sent out by De Lesseps and the Suez Canal Company, to make
                    survey of the Isthmus of Kraw, in the interest of a projected ship canal uniting
                    the waters of the Bay of Bengal and the Gulf of Siam, have, it is understood by
                    those who know, completed their work, and gone home.</p>
                <p>It is safe to affirm that they report <hi rend="italic">against</hi> the
                    practicability of the scheme.</p>
                <p>I have, &amp;c.,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>JOHN A. HALDERMAN.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
